INSTALL
-------

This project performs edge detection using CUDA and NPP (NVIDIA Performance Primitives) on GPU.
It supports two image datasets: STL-10 (Stanford) and USCSIPI (USC Signal and Image Processing Institute).

## Requirements

- Docker
- A CUDA-capable NVIDIA GPU

---

## 1. Build the Docker image

From the project root, run:

```sh
docker compose build
```

This will build the image defined in `Dockerfile` using the base image `nvidia/cuda:13.1.1-cudnn-devel-ubuntu22.04`.
The build may take several minutes the first time, as it downloads the base CUDA image and sets up the environment.

The image includes:
- A Conda environment (`npp_env`) with all required Python packages
- The `libfreeimage` library for image I/O
- The **UtilsNPP** helper files from the [NVIDIA CUDA Samples](https://github.com/NVIDIA/cuda-samples) repository,
  which is the NPP utility library suggested in the *CUDA at Scale for the Enterprise* course.
  These are installed at `/usr/local/cuda/samples/`.

---

## 2. Start the container

To launch an interactive shell inside the container, run:

```sh
docker compose run npp-dev
```

This starts the container `cuda_project_workspace` with the project directory mounted at `/root/edge-detection-cuda`.
The Conda environment `npp_env` is activated automatically.

### Optional: attach with VS Code Dev Containers

If you use Visual Studio Code, you can attach to the running container using the
[Dev Containers](https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=ms-vscode-remote.remote-containers) extension:

1. Open the Command Palette (`Ctrl+Shift+P` / `Cmd+Shift+P`).
2. Select **Dev Containers: Attach to Running Container...**
3. Choose `cuda_project_workspace`.

This gives you a full IDE experience inside the container. It is optional â€” you can always interact
with the container using standard Docker commands:

```sh
docker exec -it cuda_project_workspace bash
```

---

## 3. Download and prepare the data (inside the container)

Once inside the container, run the provided Python script to download and extract both datasets.
This may take several minutes depending on your internet connection.

```sh
python3 download-data.py
```

This will download and process:

- **STL-10** dataset from Stanford (~2.5 GB): saved as JPG images under `data/stl10_images/`
- **USCSIPI** dataset from USC SIPI (`aerials` and `misc` subsets): saved under `data/uscsipi_images/`

The `data/` folder is tracked in the repository (via `.gitkeep`), but its contents (images and archives) are ignored by Git.

---

## Execution

Instructions for building and running the edge detection programs are in `README.md`.
